Docker Image Security Scanning and Vulnerability Management
Objectives
Design and deploy a multi-tool vulnerability scanning pipeline that ingests Docker images and produces structured, machine-readable reports
Implement a policy enforcement layer that programmatically accepts or rejects images based on configurable severity thresholds
Construct a GitHub Actions CI/CD workflow that gates container image promotion on passing security scan results
Prerequisites
Proficiency with Linux command-line tools including file redirection, process management, and shell scripting
Familiarity with Docker concepts: images, layers, Dockerfiles, and the image build process
Working knowledge of JSON data structures and at least one JSON-processing tool such as jq
Lab Environment
You will work on a dedicated AWS EC2 Ubuntu instance provided by Al Nafi. The instance has a base Ubuntu installation; you will install all required tools in Task 1.

Task 1: Environment Setup â Install and Verify the Security Scanning Toolchain
Step 1.1: Install System Dependencies, Trivy, and Grype
Your instance needs three tools: Trivy (a vulnerability scanner that inspects image layers against CVE databases), Grype (an independent scanner from Anchore that cross-references its own database), and jq (a command-line JSON processor used to parse scan output).

Install system dependencies first, then add the Trivy APT repository using a heredoc to avoid line-continuation issues inside single-quoted strings, then install Grype via its installer script.

sudo apt-get update -y
sudo apt-get install -y curl wget gnupg lsb-release apt-transport-https ca-certificates jq
# Add Trivy signing key
sudo mkdir -p /etc/apt/keyrings
wget -qO - https://aquasecurity.github.io/trivy-repo/deb/public.key \
  | gpg --dearmor \
  | sudo tee /etc/apt/keyrings/trivy.gpg > /dev/null
# Official guide: https://aquasecurity.github.io/trivy/latest/getting-started/installation/

sudo tee /etc/apt/sources.list.d/trivy.list <<EOF
deb [signed-by=/etc/apt/keyrings/trivy.gpg] https://aquasecurity.github.io/trivy-repo/deb $(lsb_release -sc) main
EOF

sudo apt-get update -y
sudo apt-get install -y trivy
Troubleshoot this step:

Error: E: Malformed entry 1 in list file /etc/apt/sources.list.d/trivy.list â the file contains a literal backslash or newline inside the deb line.
Inspect the file with cat /etc/apt/sources.list.d/trivy.list; it must be a single unbroken line; delete it with sudo rm /etc/apt/sources.list.d/trivy.list and recreate using the heredoc above.
Official reference: https://aquasecurity.github.io/trivy/latest/getting-started/installation/
curl -fsSL https://raw.githubusercontent.com/anchore/grype/main/install.sh \
  | sudo sh -s -- -b /usr/local/bin
# Official guide: https://github.com/anchore/grype#installation
Troubleshoot this step:

Error: curl: (22) The requested URL returned error: 404 â the installer URL has changed upstream.
Visit https://github.com/anchore/grype/releases and download the latest grype_*_linux_amd64.tar.gz asset manually, then move the binary to /usr/local/bin/grype.
Official reference: https://github.com/anchore/grype#installation
Verify both tools respond correctly before proceeding:

trivy --version
grype version
jq --version
Expected output: each command prints a version string with no errors. If any command returns command not found, the binary is not on PATH â confirm the install path with which trivy and which grype.

Step 1.2: Install Docker Engine
Docker Engine is the container runtime. Install it using the official convenience script, then add your user to the docker group so subsequent commands do not require sudo.

curl -fsSL https://get.docker.com -o /tmp/get-docker.sh
# Official guide: https://docs.docker.com/engine/install/ubuntu/
sudo sh /tmp/get-docker.sh
sudo usermod -aG docker "$USER"
newgrp docker
Troubleshoot this step:

Error: permission denied while trying to connect to the Docker daemon socket after running docker ps.
Confirm group membership with groups; if docker is absent, log out and back in, or run exec su -l "$USER" to reload the session.
Official reference: https://docs.docker.com/engine/install/linux-postinstall/
Verify Docker is operational:

docker version
docker run --rm hello-world
Expected output: docker version prints both Client and Server sections; hello-world prints the "Hello from Docker!" message and exits cleanly.

Task 2: Pull Target Images and Build a Structured Vulnerability Report Pipeline
Step 2.1: Pull a Vulnerability Contrast Set and Scan with Both Tools
Pull four images that represent a deliberate security contrast: an end-of-life Ubuntu base, a current Ubuntu base, a full Node.js image, and its Alpine-based equivalent. Alpine Linux is a minimal distribution that ships far fewer packages, which reduces the number of potential vulnerable components.

Your requirement is to pull all four images and produce one Trivy JSON report and one Grype JSON report for each image, storing all eight files under a reports/ directory with filenames that encode the image name and scanner (for example, reports/ubuntu-18.04-trivy.json).

docker pull ubuntu:18.04
docker pull ubuntu:22.04
docker pull node:18
docker pull node:18-alpine
